Building a Spring Boot Reference Documentation Assistant with Spring AI & GPT-4
    Actually all of these llms have training data that run up to a certain point, but at some point that training data is cut off, so what if you had something like the spring boot reference documentation that is always being updated. We don't want to ask the normal chatgpt questions because that training data runs up to certain duration, but we want the latest and up-to-date documentation so that we can ask questions 
    So what we're going to do is build a spring boot reference docs assistant that will be able to answer questions. So we're going to take a large single PDF reference documentation and we're going to put that into a vector database, so we're going to use a PGVector database, so when we ask question it can do a search against that Vector database and basically pass some context to the llm when asking these questions. 

Prerequestie
1. Install Postgresql 13 version

2. Install PgVector db 
         Regular database store data like names, numbers, and dates. But today, we also need to work with more complex data like text for conversation, image, and search queries. These types
of data are often turned into vectors which are listed as a number that computers can understand. Vectors help machines make decisions, answer questions, and find things that
are similar in meaning. This is where PG vector comes very useful. 
       Postgres SQL to store structured data (ie) data that fits into tables with rows and columns. But with the rise of artificial intelligence and machine learning, we also want to store vector data which is less structured. This is where PG vector comes in. 
       PG vector is a special add-on or extensions for Postgres SQL. It lets you store and search vector embeddings in your database. A vector is just a list of numbers like 0.1, 0.2 or 0.3 that represents something like sentence, a photo or even a sounds. These vectors are created by AI models such as open AI, chatGPT, BERT or clip. 
       For example, if you have a sentence like, "How is the weather today?" an AI model can turn it to into a vector. Then if someone else asks a similar questions like, "What's the weather like?" Now, the model can compare both vectors and see that they are close in meaning even if the words are different. PG vector allows you to save these vectors in postgres tables, but it doesn't just store them. It also search and compare them using similarity measures like cosine distance and inner product. These methods helps you find items that are most similar to each other. 

Benefits of PGVector
1. One of the biggest benefits of PG vector is that it lets you store vector data directly into your Postgres SQL database. You don't need to use a different system or learn a new tool. So this makes it easier to manage your data especially when you are working on projects that involve artificial intelligence or machine learning. 

2. Next, search for similar results. PG vector makes it possible to search by meaning not just words. This is called semantic search. For example, if you search for how to learn phyon, the database can return results like beginner's guide to phyton programming, because the meaning are
similar even if the words are not the same. This is much better than keyword search which only looks for exact words.
      Semantic search helps you build smarter apps such as intelligent chat bots, help centers, or search engines. 

3. Next, index support for faster searches. PG Vector allows you to create indexes on your
vector columns. An index is like a shortcut that helps the database find data quickly. When your database has thousands or millions of vectors, searches can be slow. But with PG vector, you can use an index to make searches more faster. This is very helpful for real-time systems like
recommendation engines where speed is very important. 

4. Next, all your data in one place. Without PG vector, you might need to use a separate vector database like Pine Code. This means extra work, extra cost, and more things to manage. With PG vector, you keep everything in Postgres SQL. You can store your text, images, labels, and vectors all in the same table. This makes your setup cleaner and easier to work with. 
    PG Vector works great with AI tools like OpenAI, Hugging Face, Lang Chain, and Python libraries. If you are building an app that uses AI, you can take your vector embeddings from OpenAI or any model and store them directly in Postgress SQL with PG vector. You don't need to change your setup or learn a new system. This makes it easier for developers to add smart features to their application such as personalized recommendations or questions answer system. 

5. safe, secure and trusted.
      By using PG vector inside Postgres SQL, you get all the safety features like backups, user permissions, and transaction support. 

6. saves you money - Using PG vector means you don't need to pay for extra services or databases. You can use your existing Postgres SQL setup. Many cloud services also support PG
vector. So you can use it with providers like Superbase, Render or Heroku. This makes PG vector a cost effective choice especially for startups, small business or personal projects. 

